ta-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1657094583320" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1657094583441" data-id="1657094583441"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1657030716163" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1657030716163"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Should you do pull ups with straps?<strong> Yes. If you want to improve your strength and are unable to perform the exercise with good form and more reps, then using <a href="https://torokhtiy.com/blogs/reviews/best-lifting-straps" class="" target="_blank">wrist straps</a> is a great way to make significant progress. However, it may limit potential gains in forearm and grip strength.</strong></p></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1656944560008" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1656944560008" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg Handstands by Torokhtiy" data-exc="Handstands by Torokhtiy"><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/98aa2690-cd0f-40db-9787-30ab19e88ec6/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/pull-ups-with-straps.jpg" alt="Pull ups with straps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1655318077242" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1655318077242"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Should you use lifting straps for pull ups?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664545460308" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1664545460308"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;">There's no hard rule about whether wrist straps are good or bad—it depends on what kind of athlete you want to be as well as what kind of goals you want to achieve in terms of strength and/or hypertrophy. Here are some of the reasons you might benefit from using <a href="https://torokhtiy.com/blogs/reviews/best-lifting-straps" class="">lifting straps</a> for pull ups.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658535828348" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1658535828348"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">1. Wrist straps for pull ups are great for muscle hypertrophy</span></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658550462361" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1658550462361" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Wrist straps can support your wrists if they're not strong enough to do pull-ups, which is great if your goal is to build a hypertrophied physical appearance since it will allow you to recruit and grow your muscles properly.</p><p>If you are just learning how to do pull-ups and want some help, wrist straps are a great way for you to get started without hurting yourself. They allow you more time under tension which means that you can build strength and muscle much faster than if you didn't have them.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664918992131" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1664918992131" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg Handstands by Torokhtiy" data-exc="Handstands by Torokhtiy"><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/de3ff763-2c16-4881-b221-b5ab4e0e22d4/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/pullups-with-straps.jpg" alt="Handstands" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658543988733" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1658543988733"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">2. Wrist straps for pull ups are great for beginners&nbsp;</span></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658550492889" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1658550492889"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>If you're just starting to do pull-ups, a wrist strap can be a great tool to help build your strength and confidence. Wrist straps are easy to use and allow you to focus on the movement rather than worrying about your grip.&nbsp;</p><p>They also provide assistance at the bottom of each rep so that you get used to engaging your back muscles throughout the exercise. If you're new to these movements, I'd suggest using them until you feel confident in your form—it's not uncommon for people who have never tried them before (or haven't tried them in 10 years) to use wrist straps for their first few workouts until they get used to the movement. As long as you don’t plan to rely on them for life, then you’re good to go!</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658543989511" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1658543989511"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><span style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">3. Wrist straps for pull ups help with form and muscle recruitment</span></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658550499658" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1658550499658"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Wrist straps are a popular way to make pull-ups easier. They can help you focus on your form, and they also do a great job of helping you recruit muscles that you might not be using if you're struggling with your grip strength or wrist mobility.</p><p>If you're <a href="https://www.tuffwraps.com/blogs/news/how-to-use-lifting-straps" class="" target="_blank">using wrist straps</a> for pull ups, try focusing on pulling your entire body up with each rep. You'll want to <a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pull-ups#why-its-worth-learning" class="" target="_blank">keep your core engaged at all times</a> while performing this exercise. You should also try to use the back and arms muscles as much as possible during each repetition to ensure that they get stronger as well.</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658548305824" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1658548305824"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Cons of pull up straps</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664552436807" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1664552436807"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;">The biggest downside to using straps is that it can actually make your hand grip weaker. When you're gripping the bar for a pull-up, your grip should be tight and firm.</p><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;"><br></p><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;">But if you're using straps, that's not how your muscles are being trained.&nbsp;</p><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;">Instead of having to squeeze hard with your entire forearm muscle group and keep it locked in place while the movement happens—which will strengthen those muscles over time—you have a degree of slack in the system. In essence: If you use straps too much, then when it comes time for real-life situations where there's no equipment available (or not enough), you might find yourself unable to perform well due to weak hands!</p><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;"><br></p><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui, &quot;system-ui&quot;, &quot;segoe ui&quot;, Oxygen-Sans, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); text-align: start;">Moreover, there's another important reason why people shouldn't use these types of attachments too often: they can be dangerous! If done incorrectly—and without proper supervision from someone experienced with these methods—they could cause serious injuries. Therefore, it's only vital to use wrist straps with caution.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664919462050" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1664919462050" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg Handstands by Torokhtiy" data-exc="Handstands by Torokhtiy"><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/8d8d5184-3d7c-4670-9c09-8432d316e757/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/lifting-straps.jpg" alt="Lifting Straps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664992814107" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1664992814107"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">How to use lifting straps for pull ups?</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1664992839422" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1664992839422"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="margin-bottom: 31px; border: 0px; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 18px; font-family: Roboto, &quot;helvetica neue&quot;, -apple-system, system-ui,